# PID Control Loops — Water/Wastewater Treatment

## Overview
Three representative control loops typical of a water/wastewater treatment
process: flow control, level control, and chemical dosing (pH) control.
Each uses a PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) algorithm to maintain a
setpoint despite disturbances (varying inflow, demand changes).

## Loop 1 — Flow control (transfer pump)
- **Process variable (PV):** Flow rate (measured by flow meter)
- **Setpoint (SP):** Target flow rate to downstream process
- **Control output:** VFD speed reference to transfer pump motor
- **Tuning approach:** Start with P-only, add I to eliminate steady-state
  error, add D only if flow is very responsive/noisy (usually minimal D
  needed for flow loops)

## Loop 2 — Level control (tank/wet well)
- **PV:** Tank level (ultrasonic or pressure transmitter)
- **SP:** Target level band (e.g. maintain between 40-60%)
- **Control output:** Pump start/stop or VFD speed modulation
- **Tuning approach:** Level loops are typically slow — favor higher
  integral time to avoid pump short-cycling; consider on/off with deadband
  for simple applications, full PID for VFD-modulated applications

## Loop 3 — pH control (chemical dosing)
- **PV:** pH (measured by pH probe/transmitter)
- **SP:** Target pH range (e.g. 6.5-8.5 for discharge compliance)
- **Control output:** Dosing pump speed/stroke rate (acid or caustic)
- **Tuning approach:** pH loops are notoriously nonlinear (titration curve) —
  conservative tuning (lower gain) near the setpoint to avoid overshoot/
  oscillation; may require gain scheduling for wide pH swings

## General PID tuning method used
1. Start with output at manual/zero, note process response to a step change
   in output (open-loop test) — establishes process gain and lag
2. Set initial P based on process gain, I to eliminate offset, D sparingly
   (only for fast, low-noise loops)
3. Test closed-loop response to setpoint change; adjust for acceptable
   settling time without excessive overshoot
4. Verify performance under disturbance (e.g. sudden inflow change) not just
   setpoint change

## Why this matters
Poorly tuned PID loops in a treatment process cause either sluggish response
(risk of non-compliance) or oscillation (equipment wear, chemical waste).
Understanding both the process behavior and the tuning method — not just
"turning the knob until it looks stable" — is what separates a technician
who can troubleshoot control issues from one who can only replace parts.
